	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">A few more posts from Gordon Wrinn</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=169935" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><A href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059363.html">Gordon you are not being consistent here.</a></B><P>

But, Gordon, by your own admission Verant has gone to great lengths to add risk to previously low-risk areas because you believe that "risk" is essential to your vision for Everquest. <P>

<B>Risk is essential to gameplay in EverQuest. However we haven't "gone to great lengths" to add risk to low-risk areas, but to essentially no-risk areas. Low risk is acceptable as long as it is low-reward. What we've been trying to fix is some of the no-risk, high-reward, areas or tactics in game.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059441.html">VERANT: Very informed opinion on how to fix hell levels</a></B><P>

Assuming you're still willing to admit hell levels are an unintentional error, here's a dead-simple way to fix them:<P>

[Snip]<P>

<B>I know you've been following this issue for some time, so I'll keep it short. They aren't broken. Increasing the level-ranged experience requirement causes a need to make up experinece in the first level of the new range. Perhaps we should have spread out that additional XP requirement over the 5 levels of the range, but the same amount of experience would be required regardless.<P>

Merely doubling the xpgain or halving the xploss in the hell level, or the level after respectively doesn't "fix" the issue, it just makes it faster to get through those levels. <P>

Though I appreciate everyone's opinion on the matter, the experience system is *absolutely not* subject to post-production changes. Leveling works as it has always worked, and will continue to work in the same fashion. <P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059443.html">Explain the goal of the vague "hole" warning in the patch notes</a></B><P>

Why be vague about it unless the goal was to cause at least some people to die for no good reason?<P>

<B>Must we really spell everything out so that there's nothing left for the players to figure out on their own? The warning given when the Hole went live was as specific as it could have been without just spelling it out.<P>

Again, like many other things in the game, being the first to explore a new area is dangerous. If that risk (high probability of death) is too severe for the reward (being first), then wait until others have explored an area before moving in.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059355.html">Verant could you explain this to me again?</a></B><P>

How do npc's see thru illusion and can tell what deity you worship? <P>

<B>Illusions hide your true race only. They do not hide your complete faction (race, class, deity, and what you've done). Though it might make more sense for it to completely hide your true identity, this is one case where the need for balance outweighs realism. <P>

Without limitations to how well illusions can work, factions would be meaningless for the classes capable of using them.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
